page.title: 01DANBY HIGH MOOR N.YORKS MOOR
page.content: One of the high points of the North York Moors National Park at 405 mts. Windswept and barren save acres of heather and sheep up for summer grazing. Fine examples of terminal morrain left by glaciers. This is accentuated by the drystone walls surrounding the fields which outline the limits of the glacial action. Apart friom the moor the remaining area is rough pastureland with a fen cultivated fields in the valley bottoms. This section contains a part of the Camphill Village Trust in the N.W. corner.
